Is Graph Bipartite? 
This repository contains a Python implementation of the Is Bipartite? problem using Breadth-First Search (BFS) and graph coloring.

A graph is bipartite if you can split its nodes into two groups such that no two adjacent nodes share the same group.

ðŸ§© Problem Summary

You are given an undirected graph represented as an adjacency list:

graph[i] = list of nodes connected to node i


Your task is to check whether the entire graph is bipartite.

A graph is bipartite if:

Its nodes can be colored using two colors (e.g., +1 and -1)

No edge connects two nodes of the same color

All connected components satisfy this condition

If all components of the graph are bipartite, return:

True


Otherwise:

False

ðŸ§  Intuition

We can treat this as a 2-coloring problem.

If we color one node +1,
all its neighbors must be colored -1.

If any neighbor is already colored and has the same color,
the graph is not bipartite.

We apply BFS because:

It naturally explores nodes layer by layer

It ensures correct alternating coloring (parent â†’ child â†’ next layer)

It handles disconnected graphs by starting BFS on every node

ðŸ”„ Algorithm Overview

Create a color array (called odd in the code) initialized with 0 meaning uncolored.

For every node:

If it's uncolored, start a BFS from that node.

In BFS:

Assign the starting node a color (e.g., -1)

Every neighbor gets the opposite color

If a conflict occurs (same-colored neighbors), return False

If all components are colored without conflict, return True.



ðŸ“Œ Key Points

BFS ensures nodes are colored correctly one level at a time.

Unconnected graphs are handled by running BFS on each component.

A conflict (same color on both ends of an edge) means the graph is not bipartite.

Works for small and large graphs.

ðŸ§ª Example

Input

graph = [
  [1,3],
  [0,2],
  [1,3],
  [0,2]
]


Explanation

Node 0 â†’ color -1

Node 1 â†’ color +1

Node 2 â†’ color -1

Node 3 â†’ color +1

No adjacent nodes share the same color.

Output

True



